shire called Duffus.","English: nickname or topographic name from Middle English <i>douvehous</i>, <i>duffous</i> ‘dovecote’, for someone who lived by or worked in a dovehouse. It is possible that the English form of this name died out in or after the medieval period.","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Duffhues</b> or <b>Duifhuis</b>: topographic or habitational name referring to a house or a farm distinguished by a dovecot (compare 2 above) and named so."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma Ruffus was born in 1161, in Armston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir William Rufus, was 22 and her mother, Isabel de Arches, was 13. She married Bartholomew de Leigh in 1181, in Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1241, in Adstone, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1161–1241":"1161–1241","1156–1217":"1156–1217","1185–1240":"1185–1240","1140–1172":"1140–1172","1148–1183":"1148–1183","1 April 1240":"1. aprill 1240","1241":"1241","11/3/1183":"1183","1185":"1185","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1161":"1161","1172":"1172","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1181":"1181","Abt 1217":"umbes 1217","1217":"1217","1148":"1148","1156":"1156","Shalbourne, Wiltshire, England":"Shalbourn